00:00:21.312 --> 00:00:23.270
PROFESSOR: Why don't we
go ahead and get going.

00:00:23.270 --> 00:00:25.420
Today what we want
to do is talk about

00:00:25.420 --> 00:00:26.650
predator/prey interactions.

00:00:26.650 --> 00:00:29.393
In particular, how a predator
and its associated prey

00:00:29.393 --> 00:00:32.860
can in principal
oscillate over time.

00:00:32.860 --> 00:00:37.700
Now in this area there's this
very important model block,

00:00:37.700 --> 00:00:40.311
a Volterra model,
that has been used

00:00:40.311 --> 00:00:41.560
as kind of the standard model.

00:00:41.560 --> 00:00:43.851
It's given us some intuition
for how this might happen.

00:00:43.851 --> 00:00:46.830
But mathematical
biologists really

00:00:46.830 --> 00:00:50.165
don't like this model very
much, because the oscillations

00:00:50.165 --> 00:00:54.010
that it give are neutral,
or neutrally stable

00:00:54.010 --> 00:00:55.440
cycles or orbits.

00:00:55.440 --> 00:00:57.520
What I mean is that
it's not a limit cycle.

00:00:57.520 --> 00:01:00.390
It doesn't have a characteristic
amplitude, nor a period.

00:01:03.170 --> 00:01:05.420
And associated with that--
and it's not a concidence--

00:01:05.420 --> 00:01:07.430
and associated with
it, what it means

00:01:07.430 --> 00:01:10.060
is that if you make sort
of very small modifications

00:01:10.060 --> 00:01:12.640
to the model, then you can
get qualitatively different

00:01:12.640 --> 00:01:13.140
outcomes.

00:01:13.140 --> 00:01:16.470
In particular, you can either
abolish the cycles-- i.e.,

00:01:16.470 --> 00:01:19.130
you can turn these
neutrally stable orbits

00:01:19.130 --> 00:01:21.190
into stable limits--
or I'm sorry.

00:01:21.190 --> 00:01:23.120
Into a stable spiral.

00:01:23.120 --> 00:01:25.824
So it may have damped
the oscillations.

00:01:25.824 --> 00:01:27.990
So it could be that the
oscillations kind of go away

00:01:27.990 --> 00:01:28.730
over time.

00:01:28.730 --> 00:01:31.680
Or it could be that you turn
them into true limit cycle

00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:32.530
oscillations.

00:01:32.530 --> 00:01:35.290
And this could just be from
very small changes in the model.

00:01:35.290 --> 00:01:37.900
That's associated with this
fact that the logical Volterra

00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:40.217
model was neutrally stable.

00:01:40.217 --> 00:01:42.050
Then we'll kind of
switch gears a little bit

00:01:42.050 --> 00:01:44.080
and talk about
these experiments--

00:01:44.080 --> 00:01:47.350
that Yoshida paper that you
guys read-- where they looked

00:01:47.350 --> 00:01:50.310
at this question of what
happens in kind of a laboratory

00:01:50.310 --> 00:01:53.450
experiment where you have
a predator and its prey.

00:01:53.450 --> 00:01:54.920
And in particular
what they found

00:01:54.920 --> 00:01:59.050
is that if there is evolution
in the prey population,

00:01:59.050 --> 00:02:01.710
that you can get qualitatively
different oscillations

00:02:01.710 --> 00:02:02.530
in particular.

00:02:02.530 --> 00:02:04.946
Instead of having a 90 degree
phase shift between predator

00:02:04.946 --> 00:02:07.690
and prey, you can end
up with 180 degrees

00:02:07.690 --> 00:02:11.830
phase shift, so kind of
anti-correlated oscillations.

00:02:11.830 --> 00:02:14.400
But also that the oscillations
could be much longer than what

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:14.899
you'd.

00:02:14.899 --> 00:02:17.240
Expect

00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:18.840
And finally we'll
say something about

00:02:18.840 --> 00:02:20.640
these noise-induced
oscillations, which

00:02:20.640 --> 00:02:22.120
I believe that
you guys have been

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:28.540
playing with a bit in the
context of your homework.

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:29.670
Is it the next one?

00:02:29.670 --> 00:02:30.870
Oh, I get it.

00:02:30.870 --> 00:02:33.650
Well, you will get a chance
to play with a great deal.

00:02:33.650 --> 00:02:35.240
So pay attention then.

00:02:35.240 --> 00:02:36.110
All right.

