00:02:54.950 --> 00:02:56.480
So this Lotka-Volterra model.

00:03:01.350 --> 00:03:04.330
There's kind of a
fun history of this,

00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:05.570
which I'll tell you about.

00:03:05.570 --> 00:03:09.857
But I just want to
highlight that there

00:03:09.857 --> 00:03:12.190
are two important things that
you should be remembering.

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:16.680
And I'm getting these two
points from Mark Kot in his book

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:18.400
Elements of Theoretical
Ecology, where

00:03:18.400 --> 00:03:21.150
he says there are two things you
need to know about this model.

00:03:21.150 --> 00:03:25.290
One is that it's a bad model.

00:03:25.290 --> 00:03:27.890
And of course you can
argue what you mean by bad.

00:03:27.890 --> 00:03:29.420
I think it's maybe
overstating it.

00:03:29.420 --> 00:03:32.790
But we'll try to be explicit
about why he might say that.

00:03:32.790 --> 00:03:35.500
But then it's sort of
profoundly important.

00:03:38.790 --> 00:03:41.260
He kind of says from a
historical perspective.

00:03:41.260 --> 00:03:44.840
But I would say that maybe
both of these statements

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:45.720
are sort of true.

00:03:45.720 --> 00:03:47.810
It's a bad model
mathematically in some ways,

00:03:47.810 --> 00:03:50.570
because it's somehow
structurally unstable, but also

00:03:50.570 --> 00:03:51.450
profoundly important.

00:03:54.150 --> 00:03:55.800
The mark of
intelligence is being

00:03:55.800 --> 00:03:58.810
able to keep two incompatible
ideas in your mind

00:03:58.810 --> 00:04:00.230
at the same time.

00:04:00.230 --> 00:04:02.120
Somebody said
something like that.

00:04:02.120 --> 00:04:02.780
More than two?

00:04:02.780 --> 00:04:04.166
OK.

00:04:04.166 --> 00:04:06.290
Well, we'll try to figure
out what we mean by this.

00:04:06.290 --> 00:04:07.750
All right.

00:04:07.750 --> 00:04:13.640
So Kot, it's a nice book
on mathematical ecology,

00:04:13.640 --> 00:04:15.530
if you're curious.

00:04:15.530 --> 00:04:23.180
The history of this is that
it was in the mid-1920s.

00:04:23.180 --> 00:04:26.860
And there was a marine biologist
named Humberto D'Ancona.

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:28.550
Does anybody speak Italian?

00:04:32.060 --> 00:04:33.550
Well, he was a marine biologist.

00:04:33.550 --> 00:04:37.190
And he had been studying the
prevalence of different fish

00:04:37.190 --> 00:04:42.080
species in fish markets, and
kind of throughout Italy.

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:45.250
So he went to fish markets.

00:04:45.250 --> 00:04:52.600
Over the course of about
R-K. For about 10 years.

00:04:52.600 --> 00:04:53.100
Right?

00:04:53.100 --> 00:05:00.300
So kind of roughly
from 1912 to 1923.

00:05:00.300 --> 00:05:02.140
Something like that.

00:05:02.140 --> 00:05:04.010
And he basically
asked, well, what

00:05:04.010 --> 00:05:05.720
is the kind of the
composition of fish

00:05:05.720 --> 00:05:09.870
being sold in all these
fish markets across Italy.

00:05:09.870 --> 00:05:12.700
And he noticed something
that was very interesting,

00:05:12.700 --> 00:05:16.060
which is that there was a
marked change in the composition

00:05:16.060 --> 00:05:19.910
between more predatory
fish as compared

00:05:19.910 --> 00:05:21.650
to more prey-like fish.

00:05:21.650 --> 00:05:24.025
And this was associated with
something that was happening

00:05:24.025 --> 00:05:25.360
in Europe around that time.

00:05:28.710 --> 00:05:30.130
World War I. OK.

00:05:30.130 --> 00:05:31.610
So World War I in the middle.

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:39.120
And what he found was that
in the middle of this period

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:42.330
there was an increase,
and then later a decrease

00:05:42.330 --> 00:05:50.601
of what he called selachians,
which is apparently

00:05:50.601 --> 00:05:53.510
a word for sharks
and shark-like fish.

00:05:57.354 --> 00:06:01.675
But for our purposes, we'll
just say they are typically

00:06:01.675 --> 00:06:02.425
kind of predators.

00:06:06.020 --> 00:06:10.500
So what he saw is that
this number of selachians,

00:06:10.500 --> 00:06:14.340
a function of time, kind
of went like this, right.

00:06:14.340 --> 00:06:18.960
Where this was kind of
roughly World War I.

00:06:18.960 --> 00:06:22.970
And he wanted to try to
understand why did this happen.

00:06:22.970 --> 00:06:25.290
Why is it that war
favors predators?

00:06:36.590 --> 00:06:39.700
Probably not just having to
do with the general zeitgeist

00:06:39.700 --> 00:06:43.390
at the time.So it's probably a
more mechanistic explanation.

00:06:43.390 --> 00:06:49.820
And luckily, Humberto was
engaged to the beautiful Luisa

00:06:49.820 --> 00:06:50.320
Volterra.

00:06:50.320 --> 00:06:50.819
OK.

00:06:56.240 --> 00:06:56.780
Oops.

00:06:56.780 --> 00:07:03.240
Engaged to Luisa Volterra.

00:07:03.240 --> 00:07:09.490
So one day mid-1920s,
our hero Humberto

00:07:09.490 --> 00:07:15.110
was visiting his girlfriend.

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:19.720
And he started chatting with
his future father-in-law, who

00:07:19.720 --> 00:07:24.240
was Vito Volterra, and
asked him this question.

00:07:24.240 --> 00:07:28.110
And luckily, Vito Volterra
was a famous mathematician.

00:07:28.110 --> 00:07:29.770
So he could write
down a fancy model

00:07:29.770 --> 00:07:31.728
and try to get some
insight into this question.

00:07:34.050 --> 00:07:37.620
So this is a case of random
personal interaction leading

00:07:37.620 --> 00:07:38.840
to something interesting.

00:07:38.840 --> 00:07:42.950
That's the Volterra--
Lotka had actually

00:07:42.950 --> 00:07:47.360
studied these equations
almost 15 years earlier.

00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:49.810
First in the context of auto
catalytic kind of chemical

00:07:49.810 --> 00:07:50.900
reactions and so forth.

00:07:50.900 --> 00:07:53.800
But then later indeed, in the
context of population dynamics.

00:07:53.800 --> 00:07:57.220
So Lotka wrote a book
in the mid-1920s.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:08:03.297
Volterra wrote an article
analyzing D'Ancona's data.

00:08:03.297 --> 00:08:05.380
And then now it's called
the Lotka-Volterra model.

00:08:08.740 --> 00:08:10.300
And we'll come
back to this thing

00:08:10.300 --> 00:08:13.770
about why is it that war
favors predators after we

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:15.580
get a sense of the model.

00:08:20.700 --> 00:08:24.650
So what Volterra wrote
down was the following.

00:08:38.080 --> 00:08:40.590
First of all, we should all
make sure we can figure out

00:08:40.590 --> 00:08:43.710
which one is the predator
and which one is the prey.

00:08:43.710 --> 00:08:47.170
So let's think about
this for 15 seconds.

00:08:47.170 --> 00:08:49.110
And then we're going to
yell it out verbally.

00:08:58.400 --> 00:09:00.640
Is y the predator or the prey?

00:09:00.640 --> 00:09:02.899
Ready, three, two, one.

00:09:02.899 --> 00:09:03.690
AUDIENCE: Predator.

00:09:03.690 --> 00:09:04.523
PROFESSOR: Predator.

00:09:04.523 --> 00:09:05.220
All right.

00:09:05.220 --> 00:09:10.610
So we have a predator
here and prey.

00:09:17.910 --> 00:09:19.960
Is the total size
of the population

00:09:19.960 --> 00:09:23.790
constant? i.e, is x plus
y equal to a constant?

00:09:23.790 --> 00:09:25.340
Ready, yes or no.

00:09:25.340 --> 00:09:25.840
Verbally.

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:28.780
Three, two, one.

00:09:28.780 --> 00:09:31.260
No.

00:09:31.260 --> 00:09:35.520
It would be a constant
perhaps if these two terms--

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:37.711
if b were equal to d or so.

00:09:37.711 --> 00:09:38.210
No.

00:09:38.210 --> 00:09:39.150
That's not even true.

00:09:39.150 --> 00:09:39.930
Never mind.

00:09:39.930 --> 00:09:40.430
Yeah.

00:09:40.430 --> 00:09:40.929
OK.

00:09:40.929 --> 00:09:43.810
I guess really what
I'm thinking about is

00:09:43.810 --> 00:09:46.680
this tells us about
how many predators can

00:09:46.680 --> 00:09:47.670
be created from a prey.

00:09:47.670 --> 00:09:49.700
But then there's also
the growth in death rate.

00:09:49.700 --> 00:09:50.920
All right.

00:09:50.920 --> 00:09:55.010
But even this act
of converting prey

00:09:55.010 --> 00:09:58.087
into a predator,
even on that level

00:09:58.087 --> 00:09:59.170
it's not conserved, right?

00:09:59.170 --> 00:10:01.980
And of course, vegetarians
like to point out

00:10:01.980 --> 00:10:09.420
that you can create many corn
burgers for the price of making

00:10:09.420 --> 00:10:10.487
a hamburger.

00:10:10.487 --> 00:10:11.320
Something like that.

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:11.820
OK.

00:10:14.420 --> 00:10:15.780
Except in the case of salmon.

00:10:15.780 --> 00:10:16.730
This is not true.

00:10:19.240 --> 00:10:20.380
Well, all right.

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:23.000
We can analyze the
ratio of d over b

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.250
for a variety of
different newt sandwiches

00:10:25.250 --> 00:10:26.410
after class, perhaps.

00:10:29.080 --> 00:10:29.780
OK.

00:10:29.780 --> 00:10:33.110
So this is pretty much
the simplest model

00:10:33.110 --> 00:10:34.840
you can kind of
possibly write down

00:10:34.840 --> 00:10:39.140
that captures this basic
idea that when these two

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:43.080
species interact, we're assuming
that there's this mass action

00:10:43.080 --> 00:10:44.290
kind of rate.

00:10:44.290 --> 00:10:46.360
That it's just
proportional to the number

00:10:46.360 --> 00:10:48.701
of the density of x and y.

00:10:48.701 --> 00:10:50.950
Now I think that in the
context of chemical reactions,

00:10:50.950 --> 00:10:54.780
this is going to be true over
a huge range of densities,

00:10:54.780 --> 00:10:57.700
and perhaps almost
even rigorously true

00:10:57.700 --> 00:11:00.590
if they are just single.

00:11:00.590 --> 00:11:03.430
There's just some x and y
that bounce into each other.

00:11:03.430 --> 00:11:06.140
And at some rate
they do something.

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:09.210
Whereas I think in the
context of predator and prey,

00:11:09.210 --> 00:11:12.670
this is on much
less firm footing.

00:11:12.670 --> 00:11:13.510
That's OK.

00:11:13.510 --> 00:11:14.870
So it's at least the simplest
thing we can write down.

00:11:14.870 --> 00:11:16.810
And of course, then we'll
have to ask, how is it

00:11:16.810 --> 00:11:18.185
that the conclusions
of the model

00:11:18.185 --> 00:11:22.210
might vary depending on the
assumptions that go in here.

00:11:22.210 --> 00:11:25.050
One thing that we've spent a
lot of time in this class doing

00:11:25.050 --> 00:11:29.670
is trying to look at a set
of equations, and in words,

00:11:29.670 --> 00:11:32.910
be able to extract what the
assumptions were that went

00:11:32.910 --> 00:11:35.030
into writing the equation.

00:11:35.030 --> 00:11:36.690
And associated
with that, you can

00:11:36.690 --> 00:11:39.660
think about all these things
about the nondimensionalized

00:11:39.660 --> 00:11:41.080
versions of these equations.

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:43.610
You'll often see the
predator/prey models written

00:11:43.610 --> 00:11:48.980
in some nondimensionalized
version, where for example, you

00:11:48.980 --> 00:11:52.230
get rid of maybe the
a and maybe the c.

00:11:52.230 --> 00:11:53.760
I think that in
many cases I prefer

00:11:53.760 --> 00:11:56.730
to just leave these terms in
here, because that way we can

00:11:56.730 --> 00:11:59.639
immediately see what
happens if we go hunting,

00:11:59.639 --> 00:12:00.680
or if we do this or that.

00:12:04.370 --> 00:12:05.110
OK.

00:12:05.110 --> 00:12:08.550
Can we try to figure
out what-- there

00:12:08.550 --> 00:12:12.250
are four assumptions,
at least, that

00:12:12.250 --> 00:12:16.180
have gone into this that are
relevant and are worth saying.

00:12:16.180 --> 00:12:17.570
Can you guys help me out?

00:12:31.367 --> 00:12:31.867
Yeah.

00:12:31.867 --> 00:12:32.950
AUDIENCE: It's well-mixed.

00:12:32.950 --> 00:12:35.387
The interaction in
terms of [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:35.387 --> 00:12:35.970
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:12:35.970 --> 00:12:36.469
Right.

00:12:36.469 --> 00:12:37.490
So it's well-mixed.

00:12:37.490 --> 00:12:40.730
And there's two aspects that
we might-- So one thing,

00:12:40.730 --> 00:12:44.310
it is certainly worth
saying that it's well-mixed.

00:12:44.310 --> 00:12:46.360
But associated with
that, you're going to say

00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:47.760
that it's because of x times y.

00:12:47.760 --> 00:12:50.120
Right?

00:12:50.120 --> 00:12:50.620
Yeah.

00:12:50.620 --> 00:12:53.470
I guess that's what I feel
you were about to say.

00:12:54.919 --> 00:12:57.340
AUDIENCE: I mean, I guess.

00:12:57.340 --> 00:12:58.020
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:12:58.020 --> 00:12:58.460
Right I guess.

00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:00.668
But I think we have to keep
these things a little bit

00:13:00.668 --> 00:13:05.730
separate in the
context of chemistry,

00:13:05.730 --> 00:13:08.620
those are maybe the
same statements, right?

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:10.324
Of course, we're
writing these things.

00:13:10.324 --> 00:13:12.740
These are just quantities that
are just functions of time.

00:13:12.740 --> 00:13:14.670
We have not included
space explicitly.

00:13:14.670 --> 00:13:17.110
So in that sense, it's
definitely a well-mixed model.

00:13:17.110 --> 00:13:22.720
But just because we're
assuming that it's well-mixed,

00:13:22.720 --> 00:13:24.834
we're not keeping track
of the state of density

00:13:24.834 --> 00:13:26.250
as a function of
position does not

00:13:26.250 --> 00:13:29.290
mean that they have to
interact with this term.

00:13:29.290 --> 00:13:32.920
And for two molecules that are
bouncing against each other,

00:13:32.920 --> 00:13:34.860
then I think that is the case.

00:13:34.860 --> 00:13:37.681
But we have to keep these
assumptions separate.

00:13:37.681 --> 00:13:39.722
AUDIENCE: You could imagine
a colony of bacteria,

00:13:39.722 --> 00:13:43.060
for example, where
they're all-- you can only

00:13:43.060 --> 00:13:45.530
prey on the outside.

00:13:45.530 --> 00:13:46.650
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

00:13:46.650 --> 00:13:47.680
Necessary.

00:13:47.680 --> 00:13:51.702
I guess what I would say is
that if it were not well-mixed,

00:13:51.702 --> 00:13:53.660
it could still be that
they interact like this.

00:13:53.660 --> 00:13:56.200
And you just keep track of
the predator/prey density

00:13:56.200 --> 00:13:57.620
as a function of position.

00:13:57.620 --> 00:14:00.270
And they could still interact
in this way, possibly.

