But you're saying that it--

00:59:38.110 --> 00:59:41.400
AUDIENCE: But if you flip it
so the fixed point is stable,

00:59:41.400 --> 00:59:44.182
then you could have--

00:59:44.182 --> 00:59:44.890
PROFESSOR: I see.

00:59:44.890 --> 00:59:45.980
That may be right.

00:59:48.810 --> 00:59:51.460
I can't remember
which direction.

00:59:54.940 --> 00:59:58.370
But I'll look it up.

00:59:58.370 --> 01:00:00.950
But if you are curious about
the situations in which

01:00:00.950 --> 01:00:04.310
these predator/prey functions
will have limit cycles,

01:00:04.310 --> 01:00:07.730
you can look up
Kolmogorov's conditions.

01:00:07.730 --> 01:00:11.440
So he basically has
these four conditions

01:00:11.440 --> 01:00:13.430
in which you will
get a stable limit

01:00:13.430 --> 01:00:16.140
cycle in the
predator/prey populations.

01:00:16.140 --> 01:00:18.640
And maybe I will.

01:00:18.640 --> 01:00:20.450
And they're surprisingly simple.

01:00:32.039 --> 01:00:33.080
They were in the reading.

01:00:33.080 --> 01:00:34.210
So you can look at them.

01:00:34.210 --> 01:00:37.790
But they're basically just these
questions of the derivatives.

01:00:37.790 --> 01:00:40.730
And they're derivatives of
the per capita growth rates.

01:00:40.730 --> 01:00:43.010
So you take those
functions, you divide by x.

01:00:43.010 --> 01:00:44.250
So it's x dot over x.

01:00:44.250 --> 01:00:47.230
And then it's some f,
y dot over y, sub g.

01:00:47.230 --> 01:00:51.740
And the derivatives of
those functions withe

01:00:51.740 --> 01:00:53.570
respect to x and y
have to be something,

01:00:53.570 --> 01:00:55.050
at least in some limits.

01:00:55.050 --> 01:00:58.990
And then you get limit cycles.

01:00:58.990 --> 01:01:01.150
But I want to talk
about the experiments.

01:01:01.150 --> 01:01:03.450
Because I think that
they were quite pretty.

01:01:07.160 --> 01:01:09.740
So this is a paper
by Yoshida, et al.

01:01:16.290 --> 01:01:27.340
This is Nature 2003.

01:01:27.340 --> 01:01:30.380
And the title was "Rapid
Evolution Drives Ecological

01:01:30.380 --> 01:01:33.031
Dynamics in a
Predator/ Prey System."

01:01:33.031 --> 01:01:34.780
Could somebody kind
of say what they think

01:01:34.780 --> 01:01:37.020
is the big point of this paper?

01:01:50.936 --> 01:01:55.560
Do you guys like the
paper, dislike the paper?

01:01:55.560 --> 01:01:56.210
Too long?

01:01:56.210 --> 01:01:57.330
Was it three pages?

01:02:00.304 --> 01:02:02.470
Although it's really only--
I mean, one of the pages

01:02:02.470 --> 01:02:03.870
is figures.

01:02:03.870 --> 01:02:06.370
And one of the pages
is essentially methods.

01:02:06.370 --> 01:02:09.000
So it's really basically
a one-page paper,

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:11.550
so it's not such
heavy lifting, maybe.

01:02:19.340 --> 01:02:19.840
All right.

01:02:19.840 --> 01:02:21.970
Maybe I'll be concrete.

01:02:21.970 --> 01:02:25.230
What features of their
predator/prey oscillations

01:02:25.230 --> 01:02:27.876
were different from a normal
predator/prey oscillation?

01:02:27.876 --> 01:02:30.000
What were the features they
were trying to explain?

01:02:37.175 --> 01:02:40.607
AUDIENCE: There's a longer
phase life between the maximum.

01:02:40.607 --> 01:02:42.940
PROFESSOR: And this is an
interesting history, actually,

01:02:42.940 --> 01:02:47.970
that these are authors-- they
took what I think are basically

01:02:47.970 --> 01:02:51.200
like samples from the Great
Lakes, or something like that.

01:02:51.200 --> 01:02:53.210
So they took a
predator and prey.

01:02:53.210 --> 01:02:59.070
So it's a rotifer algal system.

01:02:59.070 --> 01:03:02.920
So the rotifer eats algae.

01:03:05.840 --> 01:03:09.937
They had previously published a
paper just a few years before,

01:03:09.937 --> 01:03:11.770
where it was called
something like "Crossing

01:03:11.770 --> 01:03:14.640
the Hopf Bifurcation in
a Predator/Prey System."

01:03:14.640 --> 01:03:17.380
And so what they did is
they had a chemostat where

01:03:17.380 --> 01:03:20.330
there was some constant rate
of dilution in their chemostat.

01:03:20.330 --> 01:03:24.100
And then they measured the
dynamics between the predator

01:03:24.100 --> 01:03:25.780
and the prey.

01:03:25.780 --> 01:03:27.980
And they showed
that depending upon,

01:03:27.980 --> 01:03:30.670
for example, the
nutrients or this dilution

01:03:30.670 --> 01:03:33.240
rate in their chemostat, they
could go from a situation

01:03:33.240 --> 01:03:38.066
where you have a
stable coexistence--

01:03:38.066 --> 01:03:40.190
so a stable fixed point
between the predator/prey--

01:03:40.190 --> 01:03:42.510
but at increasing dilution
rate, they started

01:03:42.510 --> 01:03:45.990
getting these oscillations.

01:03:45.990 --> 01:03:49.070
So they went from
stable to oscillations.

01:03:49.070 --> 01:03:50.880
And then at higher
dilution rates,

01:03:50.880 --> 01:03:54.330
they got collapse of this
predator/prey system.

01:03:54.330 --> 01:03:56.590
So this is crossing the
so-called Hopf bifurcation,

01:03:56.590 --> 01:03:59.350
where you go from
stable to unstable.

01:03:59.350 --> 01:04:03.440
So they could actually see that
they could use a simple model

01:04:03.440 --> 01:04:04.910
to try to get some
insight into why

01:04:04.910 --> 01:04:06.737
it is that a predator/prey
system might oscillate

01:04:06.737 --> 01:04:07.950
or it might not oscillate.

01:04:10.880 --> 01:04:12.040
And so that was great.

01:04:12.040 --> 01:04:13.790
But there were some
features in their data

01:04:13.790 --> 01:04:16.220
that they didn't understand.

01:04:16.220 --> 01:04:21.090
So the features were
that the oscillations

01:04:21.090 --> 01:04:22.280
had a really long period.

01:04:25.030 --> 01:04:26.100
Long period oscillations.

01:04:35.360 --> 01:04:37.820
And in all this data,
it's a little bit hard

01:04:37.820 --> 01:04:42.550
to get the exact phase lag,
but in many of the cases

01:04:42.550 --> 01:04:45.830
they saw that the
predator and prey were not

01:04:45.830 --> 01:04:49.380
at this 90 degrees out of
phase like you would expect.

01:04:49.380 --> 01:04:51.930
And in particular,
for the predator/prey,

01:04:51.930 --> 01:04:56.380
given that you have x and y, and
it's going around some circle,

01:04:56.380 --> 01:05:01.840
the idea is that first
the prey population peaks.

01:05:01.840 --> 01:05:07.080
And then kind of 90
degrees later phase,

01:05:07.080 --> 01:05:09.960
you get a peak of the predator.

01:05:09.960 --> 01:05:15.190
And you can imagine that
in any predator/prey model

01:05:15.190 --> 01:05:17.265
that you write down,
not just Lotka-Volterra,

01:05:17.265 --> 01:05:19.140
but if you write down
a differential equation

01:05:19.140 --> 01:05:23.980
with some x and some y,
it's hard to get something

01:05:23.980 --> 01:05:25.800
where it looks much different.

01:05:25.800 --> 01:05:28.740
Of course, you can imagine
maybe funny orbits or something

01:05:28.740 --> 01:05:29.920
like that.

01:05:29.920 --> 01:05:36.040
But generically you really
expect this 90 degree phase

01:05:36.040 --> 01:05:38.320
lag of the predator
relative to the prey.

01:05:41.137 --> 01:05:42.720
Whereas in the
experiments, they often

01:05:42.720 --> 01:05:57.204
saw 180 degree lag, lack of
predator relative to the prey.

01:05:57.204 --> 01:05:57.704
Yes.

01:05:57.704 --> 01:06:00.184
AUDIENCE: So when you
say [INAUDIBLE] theory

01:06:00.184 --> 01:06:02.664
of oscillation,
what does that mean?

01:06:02.664 --> 01:06:04.650
What's the time scale?

01:06:04.650 --> 01:06:05.517
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:06:05.517 --> 01:06:08.380
AUDIENCE: What would make
this suprisingly [INAUDIBLE]?

01:06:08.380 --> 01:06:09.251
PROFESSOR: Right.

01:06:09.251 --> 01:06:09.750
Yeah.

01:06:09.750 --> 01:06:09.930
OK.

01:06:09.930 --> 01:06:11.805
So this is really in
the context of-- I mean,

01:06:11.805 --> 01:06:14.800
they wrote down a model
where they did basically have

01:06:14.800 --> 01:06:18.514
something like this, where
they said there's some--

01:06:18.514 --> 01:06:21.340
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:06:21.340 --> 01:06:22.830
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:06:22.830 --> 01:06:25.390
And in particular the
predator, I think,

01:06:25.390 --> 01:06:27.260
was not really
dying on it's own.

01:06:27.260 --> 01:06:29.300
Except for the dilution.

01:06:29.300 --> 01:06:32.920
So it's really the dilution rate
from the chemostat gave them c.

01:06:32.920 --> 01:06:35.570
And they could see that indeed,
the rotifer wasn't dying much.

01:06:35.570 --> 01:06:37.150
And then a is telling
you about what

01:06:37.150 --> 01:06:39.834
happens if you don't
have the rotifer,

01:06:39.834 --> 01:06:41.000
you don't have the predator.

01:06:41.000 --> 01:06:42.680
And then at that
dilution rate, you

01:06:42.680 --> 01:06:45.050
ask what the division rate is.

01:06:45.050 --> 01:06:47.530
And that's essentially
the growth rate

01:06:47.530 --> 01:06:50.360
of that prey population
minus the dilution

01:06:50.360 --> 01:06:51.560
rate of the chemostat.

01:06:51.560 --> 01:06:54.880
I'd say that they had these
parameters pretty well.

01:07:01.620 --> 01:07:02.120
Yes.

01:07:02.120 --> 01:07:07.740
And what they saw experimentally
was that it took much longer.

01:07:07.740 --> 01:07:12.264
I mean, the period was
5 times, 10 times longer

01:07:12.264 --> 01:07:13.680
than what they
would have expected

01:07:13.680 --> 01:07:17.810
based on the measured parameters
for the predator and the prey.

01:07:24.980 --> 01:07:27.140
And of course, that
was annoying for them,

01:07:27.140 --> 01:07:29.400
because they're actually
doing the experiments.

01:07:29.400 --> 01:07:31.483
So they had to do these
chemostat experiments that

01:07:31.483 --> 01:07:33.660
lasted six months or
something like that, in order

01:07:33.660 --> 01:07:35.770
to see a couple oscillations.

01:07:35.770 --> 01:07:40.120
And so this longer period
wasn't just a mathematical--

01:07:40.120 --> 01:07:42.270
I'm sure that they were
disappointed to see

01:07:42.270 --> 01:07:44.734
these really long time-scale
oscillations, because it was

01:07:44.734 --> 01:07:46.650
something that made it
very difficult for them

01:07:46.650 --> 01:07:47.608
to do the measurements.

01:07:51.940 --> 01:07:54.670
But this is what they
saw experimentally.

01:07:54.670 --> 01:07:57.970
And they didn't know
what was causing it.

01:07:57.970 --> 01:08:02.600
But they later then
did more modeling

01:08:02.600 --> 01:08:05.880
where they asked, which
of the assumptions

01:08:05.880 --> 01:08:09.200
in our original model
might not be true.

01:08:09.200 --> 01:08:10.685
And the nature of
these things is

01:08:10.685 --> 01:08:12.060
that there are an
infinite number

01:08:12.060 --> 01:08:16.380
of things are true that are
not incorporated in the model.

01:08:16.380 --> 01:08:17.939
And this makes it
quite challenging

01:08:17.939 --> 01:08:19.569
to isolate what the
effects might be.

01:08:19.569 --> 01:08:22.960
But at the very least what
they can do is they can go in.

01:08:22.960 --> 01:08:24.944
And they have some
sense of their system.

01:08:24.944 --> 01:08:26.319
And they can make
guesses of what

01:08:26.319 --> 01:08:27.960
might have been the
primary things missing.

01:08:27.960 --> 01:08:29.290
And then they kind of
went through the models

01:08:29.290 --> 01:08:30.749
and they asked,
well, if we kind of

01:08:30.749 --> 01:08:32.498
change this assumption
or that assumption,

01:08:32.498 --> 01:08:34.439
what does it do in terms
of the oscillations.

01:08:34.439 --> 01:08:37.729
And then what they found
in a modeling paper--

01:08:37.729 --> 01:08:41.779
so this is their previous
experimental paper before this.

01:08:41.779 --> 01:08:46.020
What they found in
their models was

01:08:46.020 --> 01:08:50.259
that prey evolution was
kind of the one thing

01:08:50.259 --> 01:08:52.100
that if they allowed
prey evolution, i.e.

01:08:52.100 --> 01:08:54.450
If they allowed
different types of prey

01:08:54.450 --> 01:08:56.029
in their prey
population that might

01:08:56.029 --> 01:08:58.840
be oscillating
independently, then they

01:08:58.840 --> 01:09:00.670
could get both of these effects.

01:09:00.670 --> 01:09:02.240
So from the models
they concluded

01:09:02.240 --> 01:09:07.420
that prey evolution
could give this,

01:09:07.420 --> 01:09:09.950
could maybe explain
those two things.

01:09:14.613 --> 01:09:16.279
These are the two
experimental features.

01:09:19.819 --> 01:09:21.064
Yeah.

01:09:21.064 --> 01:09:22.540
AUDIENCE: It might
be that you have

01:09:22.540 --> 01:09:24.508
[INAUDIBLE] symantic point.

01:09:24.508 --> 01:09:29.889
If you have two types of
species, pre-species--

01:09:29.889 --> 01:09:34.116
[INAUDIBLE] they have
these characteristics

01:09:34.116 --> 01:09:36.044
and they're not evolving.

01:09:36.044 --> 01:09:37.490
They're just fixed.

01:09:37.490 --> 01:09:38.356
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:09:38.356 --> 01:09:39.939
AUDIENCE: You would
still be able to--

01:09:39.939 --> 01:09:40.479
PROFESSOR: Exactly.

01:09:40.479 --> 01:09:40.979
Right.

01:09:40.979 --> 01:09:41.826
This is a major--

01:09:41.826 --> 01:09:42.700
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:09:42.700 --> 01:09:43.160
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:09:43.160 --> 01:09:45.618
You can argue about what you
want to call evolution and not

01:09:45.618 --> 01:09:47.359
revolution.

01:09:47.359 --> 01:09:51.350
Over these time scales what
they are not looking at

01:09:51.350 --> 01:09:55.070
is the de novo kind of emergence
of new mutants spreading

01:09:55.070 --> 01:09:55.990
in the population.

01:09:55.990 --> 01:10:00.410
What they're looking at
is variations in say,

01:10:00.410 --> 01:10:03.703
different types of prey.

01:10:03.703 --> 01:10:08.020
AUDIENCE: So is that what
we would call evolution?

01:10:08.020 --> 01:10:09.450
PROFESSOR: Well, OK.

01:10:09.450 --> 01:10:10.700
This is a major question.

01:10:10.700 --> 01:10:13.926
I think different people call
evolution different things.

01:10:13.926 --> 01:10:15.550
And in particular
there's a distinction

01:10:15.550 --> 01:10:22.100
between the ecologists and
the evolutionary biologists,

01:10:22.100 --> 01:10:24.250
or evolutionary
microbiologists, or whatnot.

01:10:24.250 --> 01:10:29.390
And this is something that
I certainly encounter.

01:10:29.390 --> 01:10:32.310
For the experimental
microbial evolution guys,

01:10:32.310 --> 01:10:35.224
I'd say that for them, if you
use the word "evolution," what

01:10:35.224 --> 01:10:36.890
they really want to
see, or what they're

01:10:36.890 --> 01:10:39.930
expecting to see is kind
of new mutants arising

01:10:39.930 --> 01:10:42.479
in the population,
spreading, fixing,

01:10:42.479 --> 01:10:44.520
and that changes the
character of the population.

01:10:44.520 --> 01:10:47.110
Whereas from that
standpoint of ecologists--

01:10:47.110 --> 01:10:50.880
and indeed, if you look up
the definition of evolution,

01:10:50.880 --> 01:10:53.660
it's some change in allele
frequency over time.

01:10:53.660 --> 01:10:56.200
And this could certainly be
a change allele frequency

01:10:56.200 --> 01:10:59.010
over time in the sense that you
could imagine this arising just

01:10:59.010 --> 01:11:03.630
from, for example, there
could be a point mutation

01:11:03.630 --> 01:11:06.470
in some gene that leads it
to do something or another.

01:11:06.470 --> 01:11:08.070
And in this paper
they didn't identify

01:11:08.070 --> 01:11:09.070
exactly what was going on.

01:11:09.070 --> 01:11:11.236
I'll tell you a little bit
about a later paper where

01:11:11.236 --> 01:11:12.540
they get a better sense of it.

01:11:12.540 --> 01:11:14.540
But at least you could
imagine it being the case

01:11:14.540 --> 01:11:16.700
that there's just a point
mutation, some gene that

01:11:16.700 --> 01:11:19.750
has some fitness defect in
the absence of the predator,

01:11:19.750 --> 01:11:22.541
but then allows the algae to
avoid the predator in some way.

01:11:22.541 --> 01:11:25.490
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:11:25.490 --> 01:11:26.629
PROFESSOR: That's right.

01:11:26.629 --> 01:11:27.170
That's right.

01:11:27.170 --> 01:11:29.080
As far as the model
goes, it could

01:11:29.080 --> 01:11:31.800
be that the prey are
really-- one species was just

01:11:31.800 --> 01:11:32.550
a point mutation.

01:11:32.550 --> 01:11:33.550
Then you'd say, oh yeah.

01:11:33.550 --> 01:11:35.420
That's kind of evolution.

01:11:35.420 --> 01:11:40.230
Or it could be two different
prey populations and so forth.

01:11:40.230 --> 01:11:40.730
Right?

01:11:40.730 --> 01:11:44.330
And depending upon what
information you have access to,

01:11:44.330 --> 01:11:46.899
you would either be aware
of these things or not.

01:11:46.899 --> 01:11:48.940
In this case, they just
look under the microscope

01:11:48.940 --> 01:11:51.790
and say, oh yeah, this looks
like an algae, or whatnot.

01:11:51.790 --> 01:11:54.040
And maybe they know that
it's the same species.

01:11:54.040 --> 01:11:58.570
But they could be different
in lots of different ways.

01:11:58.570 --> 01:12:01.830
And I think this
discussion is highlighting

01:12:01.830 --> 01:12:07.290
that a lot of the same effects
that you see in ecology also

01:12:07.290 --> 01:12:09.420
you see in evolution
and vice versa.

01:12:09.420 --> 01:12:15.019
And depending upon
your focus, you

01:12:15.019 --> 01:12:17.060
might want to put it more
in the bin of evolution

01:12:17.060 --> 01:12:18.850
or in terms of
population dynamics.

01:12:18.850 --> 01:12:23.890
I think that's a matter of
taste at some point, actually.

01:12:23.890 --> 01:12:24.390
Yeah.

01:12:24.390 --> 01:12:25.764
Because they say
rapid evolution.

01:12:25.764 --> 01:12:27.001
And I think--

01:12:29.800 --> 01:12:31.302
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

01:12:31.302 --> 01:12:32.260
PROFESSOR: Yeah, right.

01:12:32.260 --> 01:12:35.352
So I think that
different people will

01:12:35.352 --> 01:12:36.560
have different takes on this.

01:12:36.560 --> 01:12:38.018
I think, once again,
this is really

01:12:38.018 --> 01:12:39.980
very much from the
standpoint of an ecologist,

01:12:39.980 --> 01:12:41.040
this is rapid evolution.

01:12:41.040 --> 01:12:45.674
Because every cycle, the
allele frequency is changing.

01:12:45.674 --> 01:12:47.340
And that's what's
maybe leading to this.

01:12:47.340 --> 01:12:49.670
But the thing is,
it's very easy for you

01:12:49.670 --> 01:12:51.720
to read certainly the
title, and come away

01:12:51.720 --> 01:12:54.270
thinking it's something
different from what it was.

01:12:56.780 --> 01:12:57.403
I agree.

01:13:00.930 --> 01:13:04.150
But one of the things I
like about this whole line

01:13:04.150 --> 01:13:06.720
of research that took place over
the course of say, 15 years,

01:13:06.720 --> 01:13:12.060
was that they did these
nice measurements.

01:13:12.060 --> 01:13:15.050
They're guided by models.

01:13:15.050 --> 01:13:17.430
They saw some things
that they were expecting,

01:13:17.430 --> 01:13:18.960
some things they
couldn't explain.

01:13:18.960 --> 01:13:20.869
And then they went
and did more modeling.

01:13:20.869 --> 01:13:22.160
And then they could explain it.

01:13:22.160 --> 01:13:26.162
And that guided this experiment.

01:13:26.162 --> 01:13:27.870
Because before what
they did is they just

01:13:27.870 --> 01:13:30.954
took kind of the sludge,
or whatever, from the lake.

01:13:30.954 --> 01:13:32.370
So there were many
different types

01:13:32.370 --> 01:13:34.360
of algae and of the
rotifer, for that matter.

01:13:34.360 --> 01:13:36.610
And then they looked at the
predator/prey oscillations

01:13:36.610 --> 01:13:37.480
between those.

01:13:37.480 --> 01:13:39.090
And then in this
paper what they did

01:13:39.090 --> 01:13:41.470
is they took individual
prey populations that

01:13:41.470 --> 01:13:42.990
came from a single prey.

01:13:42.990 --> 01:13:45.619
So they were kind of isogenic.

01:13:45.619 --> 01:13:48.160
Of course eventually they would
evolve, and blah, blah, blah.

01:13:48.160 --> 01:13:51.190
But in this case they
took individual isolates

01:13:51.190 --> 01:13:52.090
from the prey.

01:13:52.090 --> 01:13:56.120
And then what they saw is that
these two features went away.

01:13:56.120 --> 01:13:58.540
The oscillation period was
more what they were expecting.

01:13:58.540 --> 01:14:01.740
And they got the 90
degree phase lag.

01:14:01.740 --> 01:14:04.160
So it's was really a
case of these models

01:14:04.160 --> 01:14:13.720
led to the experiments where
they took kind of clonal prey.

01:14:13.720 --> 01:14:16.160
And then they recovered
their classical predictions.

01:14:27.440 --> 01:14:31.172
And indeed, they've recently
done some other measurements

01:14:31.172 --> 01:14:32.380
that I think were quite nice.

01:14:32.380 --> 01:14:35.760
They had an ecology letters
paper just a couple years ago

01:14:35.760 --> 01:14:42.450
where what they did is they
took two different algae that

01:14:42.450 --> 01:14:47.310
had different types embodying
these trade-offs that we

01:14:47.310 --> 01:14:48.530
were talking about.

01:14:48.530 --> 01:14:53.970
In particular, one of the
algae can divide rapidly.

01:14:53.970 --> 01:14:55.840
But it kind of
exists as singles.

01:14:55.840 --> 01:15:01.240
Another algae is kind of clumpy.

01:15:01.240 --> 01:15:04.920
So this algal type was
able to divide more rapidly

01:15:04.920 --> 01:15:06.220
than this algal type.

01:15:06.220 --> 01:15:12.070
But this type was harder to
eat just because it was clumpy.

01:15:12.070 --> 01:15:12.630
OK?

01:15:12.630 --> 01:15:18.220
It's one of things that once
you hear it, you say, oh yeah.

01:15:18.220 --> 01:15:18.780
Sure.

01:15:18.780 --> 01:15:24.510
But then in the abstract,
when you read this 2003 paper,

01:15:24.510 --> 01:15:27.720
you think, oh, I can't
imagine what kind of behavior

01:15:27.720 --> 01:15:31.190
could possibly help the
algae avoid these rotifers.

01:15:31.190 --> 01:15:34.710
But then in this ecology
letters paper, what they did

01:15:34.710 --> 01:15:38.070
is they actually tracked
population densities

01:15:38.070 --> 01:15:42.090
of this type, this type, and
of the rotifer over time.

01:15:42.090 --> 01:15:46.024
So then they could see all three
sub-populations oscillating.

01:15:46.024 --> 01:15:47.440
So then you can
really kind of see

01:15:47.440 --> 01:15:51.710
how this evolution, if you
want, or you could just say it's

01:15:51.710 --> 01:15:52.210
ecology.

01:15:52.210 --> 01:15:54.620
Because it could be different
species for all we care.

01:15:56.970 --> 01:16:02.380
But in any case, it's certainly
prey heterogeneity anyway you

01:16:02.380 --> 01:16:02.880
look at it.

01:16:02.880 --> 01:16:04.296
Whether it's
evolution or ecology.

01:16:04.296 --> 01:16:07.930
It's heterogeneity in
the prey population that

01:16:07.930 --> 01:16:11.194
leads to these
very qualitatively

01:16:11.194 --> 01:16:12.610
different population
oscillations.

