01:16:24.550 --> 01:16:26.620
I'll say something
about this question

01:16:26.620 --> 01:16:29.040
of noise-induced oscillations.

01:16:29.040 --> 01:16:31.890
This is going to
be something you're

01:16:31.890 --> 01:16:35.630
going to be playing
with over the next week.

01:16:35.630 --> 01:16:39.940
So you'll be experts eventually.

01:16:39.940 --> 01:16:42.300
And the discussion
in the homework

01:16:42.300 --> 01:16:44.680
is really guided by this
paper by McKane and Newman.

01:16:49.290 --> 01:16:50.830
All right.

01:16:50.830 --> 01:16:51.570
So McKane.

01:16:51.570 --> 01:16:53.200
Newman.

01:16:53.200 --> 01:16:56.300
McKane is a professor
at Manchester.

01:16:56.300 --> 01:17:03.360
And what they showed is that
if you take this model here,

01:17:03.360 --> 01:17:06.560
did this model have
limit cycle oscillations,

01:17:06.560 --> 01:17:08.520
sustained oscillations?

01:17:08.520 --> 01:17:09.560
No.

01:17:09.560 --> 01:17:12.160
So this model where we
include the carrying

01:17:12.160 --> 01:17:13.920
capacity of the
prey, this does not

01:17:13.920 --> 01:17:15.380
have sustained oscillations.

01:17:15.380 --> 01:17:23.350
So you take a model like this
that just has a stable spiral.

01:17:23.350 --> 01:17:26.200
Now this is a model in
the context of-- it's

01:17:26.200 --> 01:17:28.270
a differential equation model.

01:17:28.270 --> 01:17:33.080
Now the question is, how
do you incorporate noise?

01:17:33.080 --> 01:17:35.730
Just the fact that
individuals give birth,

01:17:35.730 --> 01:17:37.140
they die at random times.

01:17:39.860 --> 01:17:42.260
The first order way that we
often think to do this is we

01:17:42.260 --> 01:17:46.270
just add some noise on to
the differential equations.

01:17:46.270 --> 01:17:50.010
So what we do is, you might say,
oh well, you could add some a

01:17:50.010 --> 01:17:54.390
to x, and some a to y.

01:17:54.390 --> 01:17:57.970
Maybe this noise should be
proportional to x or something.

01:17:57.970 --> 01:18:00.000
So you could think about
the strength of this

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:02.180
might be some pre-factor.

01:18:02.180 --> 01:18:05.550
So you could just take kind
of a [INAUDIBLE] approach

01:18:05.550 --> 01:18:08.480
where you add noise onto
the differential equations.

01:18:08.480 --> 01:18:11.800
And then what you
get is a noisy kind

01:18:11.800 --> 01:18:16.155
of path to that fixed point.

01:18:16.155 --> 01:18:21.940
The perhaps surprising thing
is that instead of adding noise

01:18:21.940 --> 01:18:24.280
to a differential
equation, if instead you

01:18:24.280 --> 01:18:26.670
start with the individual
based approach,

01:18:26.670 --> 01:18:28.300
and you take kind
of a master equation

01:18:28.300 --> 01:18:30.810
approach where you say
they're individuals

01:18:30.810 --> 01:18:32.420
and they're doing something.

01:18:32.420 --> 01:18:35.740
Individual predators are eating
individual prey, et cetera.

01:18:35.740 --> 01:18:44.160
So if instead you take
a master equation,

01:18:44.160 --> 01:18:48.210
just like what we
did for the chemical

01:18:48.210 --> 01:18:50.406
equations modeling
the cells and so forth

01:18:50.406 --> 01:18:52.530
that we talked about at
the beginning of the class,

01:18:52.530 --> 01:18:55.780
if you formulate this
predator/prey system

01:18:55.780 --> 01:19:00.460
as an underlying set of kind of
individual based interactions,

01:19:00.460 --> 01:19:04.720
then what you actually find is
that you get surprisingly large

01:19:04.720 --> 01:19:08.250
sustained oscillations.

01:19:08.250 --> 01:19:09.800
So you really end
up with a situation

01:19:09.800 --> 01:19:11.350
where this thing comes.

01:19:11.350 --> 01:19:14.580
And it's noisy, of course.

01:19:14.580 --> 01:19:17.450
But it kind of comes
around here in some way

01:19:17.450 --> 01:19:20.200
that looks like this.

01:19:20.200 --> 01:19:24.380
And you'll see this in your
simulations next week where--

01:19:24.380 --> 01:19:26.750
and I don't know if you
can see this at all.

01:19:26.750 --> 01:19:30.590
But this is some plots
of predator and prey

01:19:30.590 --> 01:19:33.420
at reasonably large numbers,
where you can actually

01:19:33.420 --> 01:19:35.520
have 1,000 predator or prey.

01:19:35.520 --> 01:19:39.880
Somehow you can get some
sort of resonant enhancement

01:19:39.880 --> 01:19:41.190
of these oscillations.

01:19:41.190 --> 01:19:42.660
And kind of what's
going on is that

01:19:42.660 --> 01:19:46.720
the demographic fluctuations
of the demographic noise

01:19:46.720 --> 01:19:49.720
excites the system
at all frequencies.

01:19:49.720 --> 01:19:52.240
But then there is a
characteristic frequency

01:19:52.240 --> 01:19:56.150
given basically
by this frequency

01:19:56.150 --> 01:19:58.180
of the inherent
oscillation there

01:19:58.180 --> 01:20:00.500
that is somehow amplified.

01:20:00.500 --> 01:20:02.000
So you end up with
a situation where

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:03.125
you get these oscillations.

01:20:06.690 --> 01:20:09.020
And they're noisy and whatnot.

01:20:09.020 --> 01:20:13.570
But it's really because it's
this particular frequency that

01:20:13.570 --> 01:20:15.280
was amplified.

01:20:15.280 --> 01:20:18.010
And just because it takes
a long time for those

01:20:18.010 --> 01:20:19.340
oscillations to go away.

01:20:19.340 --> 01:20:23.580
So you can imagine that the
amplitude of the oscillation

01:20:23.580 --> 01:20:26.020
falls off as kind of
a root end scaling,

01:20:26.020 --> 01:20:29.130
because it's kind of a
demographic type noise.

01:20:29.130 --> 01:20:31.715
So it is true that
the relative amplitude

01:20:31.715 --> 01:20:33.940
of these oscillations,
it gets larger as you

01:20:33.940 --> 01:20:35.890
to smaller population sizes.

01:20:35.890 --> 01:20:40.850
But it still ends up being
a surprisingly large effect.

01:20:40.850 --> 01:20:43.910
And you'll see how this plays
out in this model that's

01:20:43.910 --> 01:20:45.680
basically guided by this paper.

01:20:45.680 --> 01:20:48.030
And this was a PRL in 2005.

01:20:48.030 --> 01:20:49.650
Incidentally, other
people have since

01:20:49.650 --> 01:20:52.010
studied how these
sorts of ideas can

01:20:52.010 --> 01:20:56.935
result in noise-induced
pattern formation, as well.

